WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.120
Hello friends, I am Isabelle Zimmerman, and I'm here to talk about some docs.

00:00:12.120 --> 00:00:16.360
And you can talk about documentation in a lot of different ways.

00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:21.920
You could talk about how to write really accessible explanations to, like, technical terms, or

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:25.799
you could talk about how to write examples that people can just, like, copy and paste

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:30.540
from your documentation, and it looks great, and it works every time.

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:36.360
But I am an open source software engineer at Posit, which means I kind of am always

00:00:36.360 --> 00:00:40.279
in the mindset of thinking of things as tooling problems.

00:00:40.279 --> 00:00:43.520
And documentation is no different.

00:00:43.520 --> 00:00:49.520
The R ecosystem has a really well-loved documentation tool called pkgdown.

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:54.480
And if you're an R user and you've seen pkgdown documentation, you probably don't even realize

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:57.799
all of the fantastic benefits you're getting from this.

00:00:57.799 --> 00:01:03.160
As a user, you log on, or not log on, you just, like, pull up a pkgdown site, and you

00:01:03.160 --> 00:01:07.639
have this beautiful index page, which is actually also the GitHub's readme.

00:01:07.639 --> 00:01:10.760
And then you have some tabs up at the top, and there's one that says reference, and you

00:01:10.760 --> 00:01:14.760
click on that to see the functions, and then there's usually something that says, like,

00:01:14.760 --> 00:01:20.519
read more, or articles, and then you go there if you need to have, like, certain workflows.

00:01:20.519 --> 00:01:25.199
And if you're a developer, you also really benefit from this.

00:01:25.199 --> 00:01:30.720
I was told that you can actually build a pkgdown site in less than one minute, and you don't

00:01:30.720 --> 00:01:31.720
have to trust me.

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:36.160
This came from Jenny Bryan, and I think it was established yesterday that we can, in

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:39.239
fact, trust Jenny Bryan.

00:01:39.239 --> 00:01:45.639
But I am in the Python space, and a little bit different than the very well-engineered

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:46.639
R world.

00:01:46.639 --> 00:01:50.519
It kind of feels like the wild west out here.

00:01:50.519 --> 00:01:55.440
When I started building this package vetiver, I really struggled to find a tool that felt

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:58.360
just right to create package documentation.

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:03.519
In fact, you could say I felt a little bit like Goldilocks, and if you're not familiar

00:02:03.519 --> 00:02:08.080
with the tale, Goldilocks is a children's story of a young girl, and she's lost in the

00:02:08.080 --> 00:02:12.559
woods, and she finds a house, and nobody's home, and I guess she just, like, decides

00:02:12.559 --> 00:02:16.199
to walk in and start messing with the homeowner's stuff.

00:02:16.199 --> 00:02:17.199
But it's super cool.

00:02:17.199 --> 00:02:21.000
They apparently left mid-breakfast, and she's going to eat all of their food, and she tries

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.960
this first bowl of porridge, and it's freezing cold.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:29.559
She tries the next bowl of porridge, and it's, like, scorching, scorching hot, and the last

00:02:29.559 --> 00:02:33.979
one is just right.

00:02:33.979 --> 00:02:38.440
She ends up messing up, like, all of the homeowner's stuff, and then she, like, sleeps in their

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:43.440
beds, and then some homeowning bears come back, and she realizes that it was the bears that

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:49.240
inhabited the house the whole time, but they allegedly live happily ever after.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:54.679
And while Goldilocks might have been, like, legally breaking and entering, we'll view

00:02:54.679 --> 00:03:00.240
this in the maybe more childlike lens of this is someone who approaches a space that they

00:03:00.240 --> 00:03:06.800
believe, maybe misled, but they believe it's been built just for them, and she knows what

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:07.800
she wants.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:12.240
Like, Goldilocks knows she wants this perfect porridge, and nothing feels just right.

00:03:13.039 --> 00:03:17.919
And when I started making my first doc site, I felt this frustration of knowing what I

00:03:17.919 --> 00:03:19.679
wanted in my documentation.

00:03:19.679 --> 00:03:25.559
I wanted something that was super maintainable, kind of offload that mental load to the documentation

00:03:25.559 --> 00:03:26.639
framework.

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:27.639
I wanted it maintainable.

00:03:27.639 --> 00:03:29.000
I wanted it to be Markdown-based.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:30.240
That would be super useful.

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:37.039
I love Markdown, and I wanted, more than anything, this documentation system to give users everything

00:03:37.039 --> 00:03:41.160
that they need to be successful when they're using my packages.

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:45.919
And because we're living in a fairytale land of docs utopia, it would also be really cool,

00:03:45.919 --> 00:03:50.119
like, if this tool didn't import a lot of weird things, I didn't have to wrangle a bunch

00:03:50.119 --> 00:03:56.600
of other dependencies, and overall, I just wanted it to allow me to have more time to

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:01.839
focus on the content of the site, rather than, like, fiddling with all of these weird settings.

00:04:01.839 --> 00:04:05.520
But the tools at hand were feeling not just right.

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:10.679
The one thing I knew I needed in this documentation system was long format docs, and that's kind

00:04:10.679 --> 00:04:15.679
of to tell people the when and the why to use different packages.

00:04:15.679 --> 00:04:18.959
And the R world really has this down to a science.

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:23.720
In fact, they have a whole name for it, called vignettes, and vignettes are great for telling

00:04:23.720 --> 00:04:25.200
a story.

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:33.720
It gives context to some sort of, like, small workflows that a package is useful for doing.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:36.440
And you can see it, you know, in these packaged down sites, you click on the articles, you

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:37.440
see the vignettes.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:43.880
And I tried to use a tool in Python that was really excellent in long format documentation.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:46.359
This tool is called make docs, and it was great to get started.

00:04:46.359 --> 00:04:50.160
It felt pretty ergonomic, and that was really exactly what I wanted.

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:52.399
I could write some markdown.

00:04:52.399 --> 00:04:57.880
But I realized, actually, my users cannot live on vignettes alone.

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:03.079
While people were fantastically prepared for, like, when to use docs and why they should

00:05:03.079 --> 00:05:08.320
be running this better code, there wasn't much intuition on, like, how to use certain

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:12.640
functions if I only had vignettes and, like, examples.

00:05:12.640 --> 00:05:15.480
So this documentation tool was not just right.

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.160
In order to get this API docs, I'd have to wrangle a bunch of extensions, and it just

00:05:19.160 --> 00:05:25.239
didn't really feel like something that I wanted to do with this docs tool.

00:05:25.239 --> 00:05:29.679
So to fill this gap, I knew I needed function references, and this is showing people how

00:05:29.679 --> 00:05:32.380
to run code.

00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:36.459
And when I write my Python scripts, I write it in a pretty structured way.

00:05:36.459 --> 00:05:39.500
You know, you define your function, you have your function name.

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:44.260
We've seen a lot of code over this conference, and you probably are almost, like, just ingesting

00:05:44.260 --> 00:05:45.260
this naturally.

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:48.279
You know, there's these parameters underneath.

00:05:48.279 --> 00:05:50.980
You see these three triple, like, quotes.

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:53.179
There's a line describing the function.

00:05:53.179 --> 00:05:54.179
There's parameters.

00:05:54.179 --> 00:05:56.179
There's a line underneath it.

00:05:56.179 --> 00:05:57.940
And then there's some, like, special indentation.

00:05:57.940 --> 00:06:02.540
It's structured in a very, very particular way.

00:06:02.540 --> 00:06:04.179
And this is on purpose.

00:06:04.179 --> 00:06:09.739
This is because there are tools out there to programmatically export this doc string

00:06:09.739 --> 00:06:12.260
into beautiful, beautiful websites.

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:19.459
Here you can see I used a package called Sphinx, and I could get my function name, the package

00:06:19.459 --> 00:06:22.660
name, you know, Vennifer pin metrics in the yellow.

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:26.299
You don't really have to read it if you don't want to, but there are, like, the parameters

00:06:26.299 --> 00:06:29.220
there as the function signature.

00:06:29.220 --> 00:06:33.940
In green, we have the description of the function, and we have the parameters with the description

00:06:33.940 --> 00:06:35.339
of each parameter in blue.

00:06:35.339 --> 00:06:37.779
It's kind of a lot, but it's all there.

00:06:37.779 --> 00:06:39.380
I didn't have to write this twice.

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:42.540
It just automatically got created into this website, and it was super cool.

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:45.540
You know, I've got this bulleted point list of parameters.

00:06:45.540 --> 00:06:47.540
Looks all right.

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:51.619
But what was lurking underneath the surface of Sphinx was the fact that this was all in

00:06:51.619 --> 00:06:57.459
restructured text, and I had to write a lot of custom Python code to maintain this in

00:06:57.459 --> 00:07:01.420
the long term, and that did not feel just right for me.

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:06.899
So although I had this doc site up, it felt maybe not ideal for me as a developer, as

00:07:06.899 --> 00:07:10.299
someone who didn't want to spend a lot of time developing my docs.

00:07:10.299 --> 00:07:16.739
So my quest for the just right docs framework continued.

00:07:16.739 --> 00:07:21.420
And right when I felt all hope was lost, I would never have the perfect porridge, one

00:07:21.420 --> 00:07:25.899
of my colleagues, Michael Chow, who works on the Cordo team and kind of the MLOps team

00:07:25.899 --> 00:07:29.820
at Posit, tuned me into a project that he was working on.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:36.459
And Cordodoc is a Python package that generates a function reference page for your Cordo website.

00:07:36.459 --> 00:07:40.980
And I am maybe, like, this is a self-appointed title, but I am Cordo's biggest fan.

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:42.420
I think it can do no wrong.

00:07:42.420 --> 00:07:43.420
It is beautiful.

00:07:44.339 --> 00:07:49.619
And I was able to have Cordo and Python docs at the same time.

00:07:49.619 --> 00:07:52.339
I was able to get beautiful API docs.

00:07:52.339 --> 00:07:57.899
We can see here with Cordodoc, I didn't make any weird translations.

00:07:57.899 --> 00:07:59.739
This is just kind of out of the box.

00:07:59.739 --> 00:08:04.700
I have the name of the function that we saw before, this function signature in yellow,

00:08:04.700 --> 00:08:10.820
the same description, and I had a really nice markdown table of parameters.

00:08:10.820 --> 00:08:16.100
So I have the name, the type, the description, and the defaults for each of the parameters.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:17.100
And this was really cool.

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:22.500
It felt like a little bit better way to ingest things rather than a bulleted point list.

00:08:22.500 --> 00:08:24.100
And I was really happy.

00:08:24.100 --> 00:08:29.980
So people had these API docs, and they also were able to write their long format vignettes

00:08:29.980 --> 00:08:31.779
in Python now.

00:08:31.779 --> 00:08:37.059
And it's just markdown, but Cordo is built to have a really pleasant experience for writing

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:39.179
technical documentation.

00:08:39.179 --> 00:08:44.739
And Cordodoc was able to let me lean into that and really put these tools together.

00:08:44.739 --> 00:08:50.700
So as a developer, I kind of felt like I was winning the lottery.

00:08:50.700 --> 00:08:52.179
It was quick to get started.

00:08:52.179 --> 00:09:00.059
I pip installed Cordodoc, I did a little bit of configuration, and then I ran two commands,

00:09:00.059 --> 00:09:02.179
Cordodoc build and Cordodoc preview.

00:09:02.179 --> 00:09:06.979
And I feel like people get a little scared when they have, like, a little bit of configuration

00:09:06.979 --> 00:09:07.979
in the middle of the slides.

00:09:07.979 --> 00:09:14.979
But I promise you, these 17 lines of code will give you a fully functioning doc site.

00:09:14.979 --> 00:09:17.380
It kind of feels like magic.

00:09:17.380 --> 00:09:21.700
And because this is YAML, it looks and feels like a bulleted point list.

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:24.900
Which means it's super literate and maintainable for me later on.

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.739
I'm not trying to wrangle scripts.

00:09:27.739 --> 00:09:32.580
I just get to put this in the Cordo.yaml file.

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:36.900
If you're a Cordo user, you realize this is just the same file you're using anyway

00:09:36.900 --> 00:09:38.859
to create your site.

00:09:38.859 --> 00:09:40.940
It's just got a few extra lines at the bottom.

00:09:40.940 --> 00:09:46.940
And if we want to go line by line of how to make a Cordodoc website, you're going to start

00:09:46.940 --> 00:09:51.020
with a YAML chunk that's Cordodoc specific.

00:09:51.020 --> 00:09:57.500
And if you want, you can have this sidebar that Cordodoc will create for you.

00:09:57.500 --> 00:09:59.419
And you actually don't really have to touch this.

00:09:59.419 --> 00:10:03.619
But if you think about how you're ingesting documentation, you kind of have the function

00:10:03.619 --> 00:10:07.299
here and a sidebar of all the other functions on the side.

00:10:07.299 --> 00:10:10.700
This is when it is being created.

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:13.700
You also have to say the name of the package you would like to document.

00:10:13.700 --> 00:10:17.479
It needs to be imported into the environment you're running this in.

00:10:17.479 --> 00:10:20.219
And then you get to create your index page.

00:10:20.219 --> 00:10:24.460
And this page is kind of like the landing page for all your functions.

00:10:24.460 --> 00:10:26.820
You're going to give it a title, like my golden functions.

00:10:27.340 --> 00:10:30.500
And a description that they are just right.

00:10:30.500 --> 00:10:34.340
It's going to be a scrollable list of all your functions separated by however many headers

00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:36.460
you would want.

00:10:36.460 --> 00:10:42.500
And underneath these headers, you list what you would like to document.

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:47.219
Here we can see I have my house function and then my Goldilocks class.

00:10:47.219 --> 00:10:51.580
And actually, if you just wanted to list your classes out, that would be just fine.

00:10:51.580 --> 00:10:58.140
But if you want to have a less nested structure and see every single attribute and method

00:10:58.140 --> 00:11:04.099
in the sidebar, you can list them out this way for a little bit of a flatter architecture.

00:11:04.099 --> 00:11:09.299
If you just wanted to put Goldilocks alone, if you clicked on Goldilocks in your sidebar,

00:11:09.299 --> 00:11:13.700
it would put all of these attributes and methods automatically in your documentation.

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:17.299
So you're not missing out on information.

00:11:17.299 --> 00:11:23.140
And with that little bit of configuration, I had a great site that looked something like this.

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:26.340
You can see on the left-hand side, we have our sidebar.

00:11:26.340 --> 00:11:32.979
We have our index page here with my title and my different pieces of version deploy.

00:11:32.979 --> 00:11:37.659
And there's monitor below, if you're familiar with the FedEver framework.

00:11:37.659 --> 00:11:43.340
And because this website is built with Cordo, you get all of the Cordo goodies just in there,

00:11:43.340 --> 00:11:44.580
which is amazing.

00:11:44.580 --> 00:11:51.099
You get to write in Markdown because you're getting all of these reference pages generated

00:11:51.099 --> 00:11:53.940
as Cordo Markdown files.

00:11:53.940 --> 00:11:56.059
There's accessibility built into Cordo.

00:11:56.059 --> 00:11:57.700
You have high contrast highlighting.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:03.900
You have accessible sizing and easily customizable alt text for any of the images inside of your website.

00:12:03.900 --> 00:12:11.020
And Cordo is able to grow from one page, like how I started with FedEver, to larger sites.

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:15.219
And while FedEver is a pretty simple and straightforward website, because I don't get

00:12:15.219 --> 00:12:21.539
a lot of joy in building websites besides this one, you can take it from other people

00:12:21.539 --> 00:12:23.179
in the Python community.

00:12:23.179 --> 00:12:30.979
Ibis is another Python package that just moved their docs to the Cordo doc framework.

00:12:30.979 --> 00:12:35.340
And they leverage a lot of this extensibility that's built into Cordo and Cordo doc.

00:12:35.340 --> 00:12:39.539
You can see that they've added some really fun highlighting.

00:12:39.539 --> 00:12:44.780
They have this bolded kind of explanation of the different columns.

00:12:44.780 --> 00:12:48.539
Their types are in gray.

00:12:48.539 --> 00:12:56.260
We've got beautiful green and teal coloring to match the rest of the vibes of their site.

00:12:56.260 --> 00:13:02.059
And mostly they were just able to develop inside of Cordo doc and make something that

00:13:02.059 --> 00:13:04.979
felt just right for them.

00:13:04.979 --> 00:13:10.419
But we're not really building docs for just us.

00:13:10.419 --> 00:13:15.299
We want users to enjoy these things as well.

00:13:15.299 --> 00:13:18.859
And Cordo doc gives you something that feels predictable.

00:13:18.859 --> 00:13:22.859
So when I was actually building this talk, I talked to some data scientists, and they

00:13:22.859 --> 00:13:27.340
knew R, and they were learning just enough Python to be dangerous.

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:33.099
And they had said one of the hardest parts of learning Python was they would go into

00:13:33.099 --> 00:13:37.739
these websites and they would expect to see, like, you know, that really structured, like,

00:13:37.739 --> 00:13:38.739
format.

00:13:38.739 --> 00:13:39.739
You know where to go to find everything.

00:13:39.739 --> 00:13:42.619
And they're like, where am I supposed to go in these Python sites?

00:13:42.619 --> 00:13:45.500
I feel lost.

00:13:45.500 --> 00:13:49.500
And Cordo doc leans on some of these lessons that are learned from package down.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:53.739
And it starts people off with kind of this index page, and then you have your reference

00:13:53.739 --> 00:13:55.940
page, and you can build on from there.

00:13:55.940 --> 00:14:01.500
So developers like me don't have to worry so much about, like, how to drive SEO or how

00:14:01.500 --> 00:14:03.580
to organize this website so people can find things.

00:14:03.580 --> 00:14:10.739
Like, I can just focus on the content so people can enjoy the package.

00:14:10.739 --> 00:14:18.539
One of the last and most magical elements of Cordo doc and the Cordo kind of ecosystem

00:14:18.539 --> 00:14:26.020
is you can use WASM elements inside of these documentation systems kind of easily.

00:14:26.020 --> 00:14:29.140
Easily in a WASM way, which is already kind of magic.

00:14:29.140 --> 00:14:32.700
So the Shiny for Python docs are also in Cordo doc.

00:14:32.700 --> 00:14:37.659
And if you scroll on to almost any one of their functions and go to the example at the

00:14:37.659 --> 00:14:42.940
bottom of the page, there is a fully functioning Shiny app running in the browser.

00:14:42.940 --> 00:14:46.500
And we've got great people in the session right after me who are going to explain a

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:49.380
little bit more about how this wizardry works.

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:56.000
But for now, I just want people to appreciate how powerful it is that you can be on a documentation

00:14:56.000 --> 00:15:01.200
system and be running code, learning this on the fly, you know, editing this Shiny app

00:15:01.200 --> 00:15:02.640
without even having to download it.

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:09.000
It is an incredible learning experience for users.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:14.119
So I have been a delighted user of Cordo doc, and I have to say a really heartfelt thank

00:15:14.119 --> 00:15:18.760
you to Michael Chow from the Cordo team at Posit, who's done all this amazing work to

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:20.919
make my life easier.

00:15:20.919 --> 00:15:28.020
Goldilocks in our lens is a hospitality story, where Goldilocks, she felt a little lost.

00:15:28.020 --> 00:15:32.200
She found a home in Cordo doc that felt just right.

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:35.200
Thank you.

00:15:35.200 --> 00:15:41.799
Thank you.

00:15:41.799 --> 00:15:44.520
We have caught up, so there is time for questions.

00:15:44.520 --> 00:15:45.520
Okay.

00:15:46.440 --> 00:15:54.359
Can Cordo doc do parameter documentation inheritance, like the Roxygen inherit params tag?

00:15:54.359 --> 00:16:02.280
I would love to have whoever asked this question talk to me and Michael Chow later, because

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:07.960
I don't know enough about the R side to understand that entirely.

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:15.119
Does Cordo doc support cross-references the way you very awkwardly can do in Sphinx slash

00:16:15.119 --> 00:16:16.640
restructured text?

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:24.799
There are cross-references, and it does so I actually I had a Sphinx website that you

00:16:24.799 --> 00:16:29.799
guys saw before I had a Cordo doc website, and it really did feel like a good, like,

00:16:29.799 --> 00:16:36.380
drop-in replacement, like I thought I was going to be feeling like, oh, no, I'm losing

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:41.500
stuff because Sphinx it feels like it has everything, like the Sphinx ecosystem is huge,

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:47.340
like I'll just install 17 more extensions, and finally my doc site will be perfect.

00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:53.340
But I felt like making this jump, I didn't lose out on any of these extensions.

00:16:53.340 --> 00:17:01.859
I got what I needed kind of out of the box with much less custom Python in my package.

00:17:01.859 --> 00:17:03.539
I'll do one more.

00:17:03.539 --> 00:17:08.780
Can you generate a default configuration YAML file automatically using some equivalent

00:17:08.780 --> 00:17:11.300
of the use this package?

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:18.420
There's not, but you can copy and paste from the Cordo doc website, which is not a super

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:23.900
satisfactory answer, but it is an answer nonetheless.

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:30.859
And I also have to plug Michael Chow, the incredible creator of Cordo doc, is always

00:17:30.859 --> 00:17:36.660
looking for people to help make new package documentation, so if you open an issue on

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:43.660
the Cordo doc GitHub repo, allegedly he will help you build your documentation site.

00:17:43.660 --> 00:17:46.540
That seems like a great place to stop, so let's thank Isabel and all of our speakers

00:17:46.540 --> 00:17:47.540
in this track once again.

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:48.540
Thank you.

